Is the name of the login button on the login form really &#39;logonbuttom&#39; 
(with an &#39;m&#39;)? (For that matter, are the username and password fields 
really named &#39;username&#39; and &#39;password&#39;?)

Log-ins vary a lot between sites. Heritrix can only log-in if the login 
form has predictable form-element-names, and setting this up requires 
careful inspection of the target login form. Even so, some sites may use 
dynamic/hidden form fields (especially nowadays as a protection against 
cross-site request forgeries) that will foil the current Heritrix login 
code.

If trying to get this to work, the HtmlFormCredentialTest unit test 
class is the best model, and you would want to debug what you&#39;re trying 
in a tiny instant test crawl of just that login form and one 
login-protected page.

If the site&#39;s design doesn&#39;t work with the very-limited Heritrix login 
capability, another option may be to:

(1) login with Firefox
(2) export the relevant cookies proving you&#39;re logged in ï¿½ I think 
nowadays this requires a Firefox extension
(3) supply that cookies.txt file to the Heritrix CookieStorage bean via 
its &#39;cookiesLoadFile&#39; property, which tells it a place to preload 
cookies at crawl-start

Hope this helps,

- Gordon @ IA

